<li>Nonstandard <strong>ἥμυσυ</strong> &lt;hḗmusu&gt; from standard
<strong>ἥμισυ</strong> &lt;hḗmisu&gt; <em>half</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/432232">p.col.3.4.xml</a>, ll. 14,
15 (Origin unknown, 258-257 BCE)</li>
<li>Nonstandard <strong>Λίβου</strong> &lt;Libou&gt; from standard
<strong>Λύβου</strong> &lt;Lubou&gt; <em>personal name</em>-gen.sg<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/412208">o.abu.mina.660.xml</a>, l.1
(Abu Mena, 601-650 CE)</li>
</ul>
<p>Egyptian did not have /y/ <span class="citation" data-cites="peust1999">(Peust 1999)</span>, the phonological development
of /y/ raising to /i/ might have been accelerated in Greek used in
Egypt. The effect of language contact related to the L2 usage of Greek
/y/ can be seen in various misspellings deriving from the impact of the
Egyptian-Coptic phonological system on that of Greek see <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/73">1.2.2 Underdifferentiation of
foreign vowels</a>.</p>
<p>A summary of the long development of the Greek vowel inventory can be
seen in <span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2010">Horrocks
(2010)</span>, p.&nbsp;160-170). From the description, it is evident that
there are gaps and uncertainties as long as centuries related to the
dating of some of these changes. The study of especially documentary
papyri, rich with nonstandard variation based on the contemporary
pronunciation of sounds, can help bridge over some of these gaps.</p>
